[[File:Trotter, Chris (Alliance).jpg|right|thumb|Chris Trotter speaking at the [[Alliance (New Zealand political party)|Alliance]] party conference in 2007]]
'''Chris Trotter''' (born c. 1956) is a [[left-wing|left]]-leaning political commentator in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=10608914&pnum=0|title=TVNZ looking at options for Paul Henry|last=Drinnan|first=John|date=13 November 2009|work=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref> He is the editor of the occasional ''[[Political Review]]'' magazine, and is a regular speaker, orator and singer at [[left-wing]], [[labor union|union]] and [[socialist]] events.

==Biography==
Chris Trotter has worked for unions and was on the New Zealand council of the Labour Party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/politics/news/article.cfm?c_id=280&objectid=10461671&pnum=0|title=Left, right, left - the march of NZ history since the '70s|last=McCammon|first=Belinda |date=5 September 2007|work=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref> He writes the "From the Left" column in the ''[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|Dominion Post]]'', and has also contributed to the ''[[Independent Financial Review]]''. He makes semi-frequent television appearances as a political commentator.

He has attracted criticism from other broad left critics who regard his knowledge of [[feminist]], indigenous and [[LGBT]] politics to be insignificant, particularly insofar as their own distributive justice dimensions are concerned <ref>http://www.norightturn.blogspot.com</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gaynz.com/blog/redqueen |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100829054049/http://gaynz.com/blog/redqueen/ |archive-date=29 August 2010 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

Trotter is the author of ''No Left Turn'', a political history of New Zealand.<ref name="nlt">{{cite book | title=No Left Turn: The Distortion of New Zealand's History by Greed, Bigotry, and Right-Wing Politics| url=https://www.amazon.com/No-Left-Turn-Distortion-Right-Wing/dp/1869418093/| last=Trotter| first=Chris| year=2007| publisher=Random House| location=New Zealand}}</ref> Novelist, poet and critic [[C K Stead]] described the book as "a dashingly written and persuasive elegy for the Scandinavian-style socialist democracy New Zealand might have been, and at the same time a realistic (though at times appropriately angry) acknowledgement that, given the forces, internal and external, ranged against it, the chances of it happening, and lasting, were never very good."<ref name="ckstead">{{cite journal | title=Our Favourite Things| journal=Dominion Post| date=8 December 2007 }}</ref>

In February 2008, he said that [[Helen Clark]] should stand down before the [[New Zealand general election, 2008|election]] and be replaced by [[Phil Goff]], who he thought may have been Labour's only hope of regaining ground with struggling families. He has since recanted, arguing that Goff should have stood down in his turn before the [[New Zealand general election, 2011]], arguing that [[David Cunliffe]] should replace him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/282462|title=Labour poll-axed |date=23 February 2008|work=The Dominion Post |accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref><ref>http://www.bowalleyroad.com/2010/08/leader-labour-needs-to-have.html{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

In July 2018, Trotter joined the Free Speech Coalition, a group of former politicians, lawyers, journalists, and academics that pursued legal action against the [[Mayor of Auckland]] [[Phil Goff]] for denying [[Auckland Council]] facilities to two Canadian [[alt-right]] activists [[Lauren Southern]] and [[Stefan Molyneux]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Free Speech Coalition website |url=https://freespeechcoalition.nz/ |publisher=Free Speech Coalition |accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Free Speech Coalition on details of legal action |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO1807/S00202/free-speech-coalition-on-details-of-legal-action.htm |accessdate=5 August 2018 |work=Free Speech Coalition |publisher=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=16 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Truebridge |first1=Nick |title=Free speech group raises $50k to challenge Auckland Council over far-Right speaker ban |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/105377682/free-speech-group-raises-50k-to-challenge-auckland-council-over-farright-speaker-ban |accessdate=5 August 2018 |publisher=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=10 July 2018}}</ref> Trotter justified his defense of the two alt-right activists' free speech by arguing that left-wing opponents of the tour lacked the courage to debate the alt-right.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Trotter |first1=Chris |title=Do We Really Lack the Courage to Debate the Alt-Right? Do We Really Lack the Ideas to Defeat Them? |url=http://bowalleyroad.blogspot.com/2018/07/do-we-really-lack-courage-to-debate-alt.html |website=Bowalley Road |accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>

