{{quotebox|''It's not no secret. Everybody knows that. The big businesses from here, if there are no drugs around, they cannot sell their articles. So when you see things are good, that means drugs are around.''&mdash;[[Bluefields]] shopkeeper regarding state involvement in drug trade<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/parallels/2014/10/26/357791551/nicaragua-follows-its-own-path-in-dealing-with-drug-traffickers |accessdate=November 7, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102180729/http://www.npr.org/blogs/parallels/2014/10/26/357791551/nicaragua-follows-its-own-path-in-dealing-with-drug-traffickers |archivedate=November 2, 2014 }}</ref>}}

'''Nicaraguan exceptionalism''' (Spanish: ''Excepcionalismo Nicaragüense'') is a belief that [[Nicaragua]] is an exceptional nation, different from its [[Central American]] neighbors, despite shared history in the [[Federal Republic of Central America]] and regional integration in the [[Central American Integration System]].<ref name="utexas">{{cite web|url=http://www.utexas.edu/cola/insts/llilas/events/32246|title=UT College of Liberal Arts|date=7 November 2014|publisher=Utexas.edu|accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref> This concept differs from the exceptionalism of other nations primarily as its basis rests solely upon the actions and institutions implemented since the [[Sandanista]] government took power in the [[Nicaraguan Revolution|1979 revolution]], and again in 2006 after passing power to the [[National Opposition Union]]. The difference here is, most nationalist claims to [[exceptionalism]] originate from the founding of nations and/or the development of their cultures due to long histories.

The widely regarded exception within the current panorama of dystopian violence afflicting contemporary Central America, Nicaragua is often hailed as "the safest (sano) country in Latin America (despite also being the poorest)".<ref name="utexas"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panoramas.pitt.edu/content/violence-migration-and-nicaragua-exception|title=Of Violence, Migration, and the Nicaragua Exception|publisher=Panoramas.pitt.edu|accessdate=7 November 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107051010/http://www.panoramas.pitt.edu/content/violence-migration-and-nicaragua-exception|archivedate=7 November 2014|df=}}</ref> Other exceptionalism claims include the concept that Nicaragua is highly resistant to [[drug trafficking]] as compared even to richer neighbors like [[Costa Rica]] and [[Panama]]. Even Western media have drawn on this notion in reporting on why Nicaraguan children are not migrating to the United States in the [[2014 American immigration crisis]] to flee drug trafficking violence (despite that there is heavy [[Nicaraguans#Nicaraguans_in_Costa_Rica|Nicaraguan immigration to neighboring Costa Rica]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/alex-nowrasteh/nicaragua-child-migrants-us_b_5592209.html|title=Why Aren't Child Migrants Fleeing to the U.S. From Nicaragua?|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref>  

